184
00:16:57,960 --> 00:17:03,860
his hand from the table. Just moving them one by one. You live in my house. You have your own room.

185
00:17:04,060 --> 00:17:10,660
I have another. Both doors stay closed. Go on. In public, you're my wife. You go to events with me.

186
00:17:10,880 --> 00:17:16,740
You smile when it's time to smile. You don't need to pretend more than that. In private? Nothing.

187
00:17:16,740 --> 00:17:22,560
I won't touch you. I won't go into your room. I won't ask about your life. And you won't

188
00:17:22,560 --> 00:17:28,860
ask about mine. No questions. No questions. I set the cup on the saucer. I thought that no

189
00:17:28,860 --> 00:17:34,160
questions had the smell of a locked door. And locked doors were exactly the ones I always wanted to open.

190
00:17:34,660 --> 00:17:40,580
For how long? One year. After that, you can ask for the separation without any contest from me.

191
00:17:40,740 --> 00:17:45,840
If you'd rather stay longer, it's negotiable. Why me? It was the first question of mine that took

192
00:17:45,840 --> 00:17:51,800
a second longer to answer. Just a second. Because you need it. His voice dropped half a tone.

193
00:17:52,240 --> 00:17:57,300
And because I need a wife for reasons that don't fit into this conversation, I held his gaze.

194
00:17:57,740 --> 00:18:02,280
He held mine. Neither of us blinked for a stretch of time that would have been awkward at any other

195
00:18:02,280 --> 00:18:08,300
table. I'll think about it. I said, you haven't till tomorrow morning. Me. He took from the

196
00:18:08,300 --> 00:18:13,700
inner pocket of his jacket, a cream-colored card with tall, firm handwriting. The address of a city hall.

197
00:18:13,700 --> 00:18:20,580
If you show up, it's yes. If you don't, it's no. I took the card. Our fingers didn't touch,

198
00:18:21,020 --> 00:18:25,620
but they passed so close that I felt the warmth of his hand for half a second before I pulled mine back.

199
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:32,460
Do you always negotiate like this? I asked, two sentences in a card? No. He leaned back in his

200
00:18:32,460 --> 00:18:38,020
chair. But with you, I didn't want to make things up. I stood up from the table. I didn't thank him

201
00:18:38,020 --> 00:18:42,600
for the coffee. He didn't expect me to. I walked to the door with my back straight,

202
00:18:42,600 --> 00:18:47,620
knowing all of Providence would be recounting this scene for weeks. When I touched the handle,

203
00:18:48,220 --> 00:18:55,320
I heard behind me, low, almost thought aloud. Two sugar cubes, a drop of milk. I stopped.

204
00:18:55,860 --> 00:19:01,420
I looked over my shoulder. What? Ludovico didn't look at me. He was stirring his own coffee with a

205
00:19:01,420 --> 00:19:06,820
small spoon. That's how you take it. When you're not testing me, I stood there a second longer

206
00:19:06,820 --> 00:19:14,100
than I should have. Then I opened the door and left. Err. I slept badly. I woke before the sun.

207
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:19,900
I shoured. Put on the least wrinkled blue dress in my closet. Gathered my documents into a small

208
00:19:19,900 --> 00:19:25,080
bag and went down the stairs without saying goodbye to a single thing. I left a short note

209
00:19:25,080 --> 00:19:30,380
for Narina on the kitchen table. The kind that explains nothing and promises everything. I'd have

210
00:19:30,380 --> 00:19:35,940
to take the scolding later. City Hall was three blocks from the harbor. I arrived 15 minutes before

211
00:19:35,940 --> 00:19:41,680
he was already there. Leaning against the corridor wall, hands in his jacket pockets,

212
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:46,180
looking at his own shoe like someone who'd been waiting long enough to have memorized the floor.

213
00:19:46,740 --> 00:19:52,200
Beside him, an older man, broad shouldered, with the look of someone who'd come back from wars

214
00:19:52,200 --> 00:19:58,120
no one had named. Ludovico raised his head when he saw me. He didn't smile. He made no ceremony.

215
00:19:58,760 --> 00:20:04,900
He just waited for me to arrive. Good morning. I said, good morning. He made a discreet gesture

216
00:20:04,900 --> 00:20:11,040
toward the man beside him. Bastion del Rose. He works with me. He'll be nearby whenever you go out.

217
00:20:11,500 --> 00:20:17,720
Bastion tilted his head half a degree. No hello, no pleasure, no smile, just the half degree.

218
00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:23,740
Nice to meet you. I answered anyway. Because my grandmother would have smacked me if I didn't answer.

219
00:20:24,260 --> 00:20:29,720
The clerk called us. We went into a small room with a long table. Papers already prepared.

220
00:20:30,300 --> 00:20:34,160
Ludovico pushed them toward me before the clerk could open his mouth. Read it.

221
00:20:34,160 --> 00:20:39,680
Slowly. If there's any claws you don't accept, we redo it. I read every line.

222
00:20:40,100 --> 00:20:45,180
It was exactly the way he'd said in the cafe. Separate rooms, appearances in public.

223
00:20:45,800 --> 00:20:51,920
No questions. One year. Right of unilateral exit on her part. I reached the last page and

224
00:20:51,920 --> 00:20:57,160
slid my finger down to the signature line. I saw nothing I wasn't supposed to see. Not then.

225
00:20:57,160 --> 00:21:03,760
It's  fine.  I  said.  I  signed.  He  signed  after  me.  The  clerk  stamped  it.  There  was  no

226
00:21:03,760 --> 00:21:05,180
kiss.  No  photo.

227
00:21:05,740 --> 00:21:11,140
No rice thrown on the way out. The three of us left City Hall in silence. The car was waiting.

228
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:17,900
Black, glossy, glass too dark. The kind my father used to tell me not to look at when I was a child.

229
00:21:18,520 --> 00:21:23,920
Bastion opened the rear door. Ludovico got in from the other side and sat next to me without saying anything.

230
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:29,300
The car took the road toward the upper suburb. Providence shrank in the window. The red rooftop

231
00:21:29,300 --> 00:21:35,460
falling away behind us and green took over. He didn't speak the entire way. Neither did I.

232
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:41,640
The mansion gate appeared after 20 minutes. Dark iron, tall, with a discreet crest in the center.

233
00:21:42,260 --> 00:21:47,600
A lion's head with the crown split in two. I didn't ask what it meant. It was part of the no questions.

234
00:21:48,180 --> 00:21:53,700
The gate opened. The car went up a lane of low trees. I saw the house before I knew it was a house.

235
00:21:53,920 --> 00:22:00,120
Three stories of pale stone, tall windows, a double staircase at the entrance. A small woman,

236
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:06,200
my grandmother's age, appeared at the door above. Her pulled into a low bun, white apron,

237
00:22:06,720 --> 00:22:14,140
dry hands, Donachyata, Ludovico said, this is Yolanda. Donachyata looked me over from head to toe,

238
00:22:14,520 --> 00:22:19,500
not with judgment, with concern. The kind of look only a kitchen woman knows how to give.

239
00:22:19,500 --> 00:22:25,680
Welcome. She said, you must be tired. I'm fine. She didn't believe me, but she

240
00:22:25,680 --> 00:22:31,580
not did and didn't insist. Ludovico took me upstairs. The upper corridor was long, with identical

241
00:22:31,580 --> 00:22:36,860
doors on both sides. He stopped at the third door on the right and opened it. This is your room.

242
00:22:37,240 --> 00:22:43,460
It was too big for one person. A canopy double bed, a desk at the window, a built-in closet

243
00:22:43,460 --> 00:22:48,540
along an entire wall. Everything in shades of cream and gray, a tasteful cold.

244
00:22:48,540 --> 00:22:53,220
My room is at the end of the corridor. He said, behind me, on the left side,

245
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:59,280
you don't need to go past it. Understood? If you need anything, Donachyata is always nearby.

246
00:22:59,900 --> 00:23:06,520
And you, he paused a second. If you need me, Donachyata knows where I am. I turned to look at him.

247
00:23:06,740 --> 00:23:11,860
He was standing in the doorway, one hand on the handle, looking at some point between my shoulder and the

248
00:23:11,860 --> 00:23:17,500
window. But the first time since the cafe, he seemed unsure of where to put his gaze. Thank you.

249
00:23:17,500 --> 00:23:22,360
I said, I wasn't quite sure why. He tilted his head a fraction of a millimeter,

250
00:23:23,040 --> 00:23:28,920
closed the door. I heard his footsteps go down the corridor, and silence. I sat on the edge of the bed.

251
00:23:29,340 --> 00:23:34,180
I ran my hand over the duvet, and the fabric was soft in a way that made my eyes sting without warning.

252
00:23:34,820 --> 00:23:41,000
I didn't cry. Not that first afternoon. That night, Donachyata came up with a tray, hot soup,

253
00:23:41,360 --> 00:23:46,980
fresh bread, a glass of red wine. I didn't ask her to swap it for water. I drank the wine to the

254
00:23:46,980 --> 00:23:51,380
last drop. I laid down without changing my clothes and stared at the ceiling of the canopy.

255
00:23:51,940 --> 00:23:58,260
Near midnight, I heard footsteps in the corridor, slow, measured footsteps. They came from the end of

256
00:23:58,260 --> 00:24:03,720
the corridor. They reached my door. They stopped. They stood there for a stretch of time. I couldn't measure.

257
00:24:04,320 --> 00:24:10,860
Five seconds. Ten. More than ten. He didn't knock. He didn't call out. He made no sound.

258
00:24:11,320 --> 00:24:16,860
Then the footsteps went back. I heard them move away slowly. The same rhythm in the direction they had

259
00:24:16,860 --> 00:24:22,940
from. The door at the end of the corridor opened. Closed. I stared at the canopy in the same position

260
00:24:22,940 --> 00:24:28,760
and understood, lying in that bed too big for one person, that the man the town feared had come

261
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:35,780
to my door on the first night. Not to come in, not to speak. Only to stop outside, and then go back.

262
00:24:36,180 --> 00:24:41,960
I closed my eyes. I didn't sleep. Chapter three. House rules, the man's gestures.

263
00:24:43,360 --> 00:24:48,240
Karachiolo mansion woke before I did. I discovered this on the first morning. When I came down

264
00:24:48,240 --> 00:24:52,720
the marble stairs still in my robe, fastened up to my neck, and found the house already breathing.

265
00:24:53,620 --> 00:24:58,500
Donachiyara, tidying the sideboard in the hall. The smell of fresh bread coming from the kitchen.

266
00:24:59,140 --> 00:25:03,340
A staff member I didn't recognize cleaning the vestibule stained glass with silent movements.

267
00:25:03,880 --> 00:25:08,160
No one looked at me as if I didn't belong there. No one looked at me as if I belonged either.

268
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:14,740
It was worse than hostility. It was professional neutrality. Good morning, ma'am. Donachiyara said,

269
00:25:15,140 --> 00:25:20,060
seeing me standing in the kitchen archway. Coffee here or in the garden room. It took me a second

270
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:26,780
to understand that ma'am was me. Here is fine. I answered. If it's not in the way, she laughed softly.

271
00:25:27,360 --> 00:25:31,320
The kind of laugh only Italian women of a certain age know how to give without taking their hands

272
00:25:31,320 --> 00:25:37,600
off their apron. You. In the way in my kitchen. That's a good one. I sat on the wooden bench against

273
00:25:38,740 --> 00:25:43,300
Donachiyara set a cup in front of me without asking how I wanted it. Two sugar cubes had been

274
00:25:43,300 --> 00:25:48,700
dissolved in it. A drop of milk had been added on top. The coffee was exactly the color I'd been

275
00:25:48,700 --> 00:25:53,780
drinking since I was 15. I held the cup with both hands. Did you tell Mr. Ludovico?

276
00:25:54,480 --> 00:25:59,400
Donachiyara kept stirring a pot on the stove without turning around. No one needed to tell me anything

277
00:25:59,400 --> 00:26:05,400
my dear. Mr. Ludovico left it noted. He asked that it be this way every day. She paused briefly.

278
00:26:05,400 --> 00:26:11,780
Always. I drank the coffee too slowly. That was how the first week went. I'd discover a house

279
00:26:11,780 --> 00:26:17,120
rule by accident. And Ludovico had already altered the rule in silence so I'd fit inside it.

280
00:26:17,320 --> 00:26:22,060
On Monday, I mentioned aloud to Donachiyara that I missed the bookside left in my apartment.

281
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:27,520
On Tuesday, three of my favorites were on the little table in my room with new bookmarks

282
00:26:27,520 --> 00:26:33,140
between the pages. On Wednesday, I told Bastion I hated the black car because it reminded me of a

283
00:26:33,140 --> 00:26:38,480
general. I only said it sarcastically because he'd appeared in a dark suit in the corridor and I

284
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:43,800
wanted to provoke him. On Thursday, Bastion appeared at the winter garden door with his hands folded

285
00:26:43,800 --> 00:26:49,180
in front of his body, with the stone face that was already his trademark. He asked me to ask whether

286
00:26:49,180 --> 00:26:54,540
you'd prefer the gray car or the black one to go out today. I looked up from my book. Do I have

287
00:26:54,540 --> 00:27:01,760
something scheduled today? You will, if you want to. He blinked once. Bastion, I said, trying not to

288
00:27:01,760 --> 00:27:08,160
where you always like this or where you trained. Both, ma'am. And he went back down the corridor with a

289
00:27:08,160 --> 00:27:13,200
step identical to the one he'd arrived with. I kept staring at the door for half a minute with the book

290
00:27:13,200 --> 00:27:17,800
forgotten in my lap. And admitted to myself that this house was starting to become an intimate

291
00:27:17,800 --> 00:27:23,800
joke I hadn't asked to be part of. The problem was, the joke had an owner. And the owner of the

292
00:27:23,800 --> 00:27:30,440
joke didn't smile. Ludovico and I crossed paths with icy formality. In the corridor, he'd nod,

293
00:27:30,440 --> 00:27:36,620
half a degree, enough not to be rude. At dinner, we sat at the two ends of the long table

294
00:27:36,620 --> 00:27:42,140
like two chess pieces pretending the board was too big for any attack. He'd ask if I'd needed anything.

295
00:27:42,720 --> 00:27:48,540
I'd answer no. He'd ask if Dona Chiara had been kind. I'd answer that she was an angel. He'd

296
00:27:48,540 --> 00:27:54,480
fold his napkin and stand up. No questions. That was the rule. He kept the rule better than I did.

297
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,120
Wednesday evening, Narina showed up at the gate with a leather bag that looked like it weighed

298
00:27:59,120 --> 00:28:04,820
more than she did. Bastion opened the gate for her without arguing. Dona Chiara hugged her like a

299
00:28:04,820 --> 00:28:09,760
relative. Narina walked through the hall with wide eyes and a comment on the tip of her tongue.

300
00:28:10,160 --> 00:28:15,280
This place looks like a museum with tasteful ghosts. I pulled her into the kitchen before Ludovico

301
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:20,920
could appear. Sweetie, she whispered, taking a Tupperware container out of her bag.

302
00:28:21,360 --> 00:28:26,780
I brought my grandmother's lasagna, not that Dona Chiara needs help, but my grandma liked you.

303
00:28:26,780 --> 00:28:32,240
And I wasn't going to let that slide. Your social hazard. I know. Where does he sleep?

304
00:28:32,920 --> 00:28:37,720
Narina. Just so I know the distance between the two rooms missing. It's field research.

305
00:28:38,280 --> 00:28:43,580
We sat on the kitchen bench, split the lasagna into two bowls, and ate in secret like two

306
00:28:43,580 --> 00:28:48,440
teenagers who'd snuck out of the cafeteria. It was the first time I'd laughed since the church bell.

307
00:28:48,740 --> 00:28:53,560
I laughed for real. My face half lowered, almost choking on a piece of cheese.

308
00:28:54,360 --> 00:28:59,840
Dona Chiara passed by the door, pretended not to see, and kept going toward the garden.

309
00:29:00,460 --> 00:29:06,780
Ludovico passed by the door five minutes later. He also pretended not to see, but I saw him. He

310
00:29:06,780 --> 00:29:12,180
had his shirts leave rolled up to the elbow, his hair a little out of place. The kind of detail I

311
00:29:12,180 --> 00:29:17,280
shouldn't have registered. He stopped in the archway for half a second. Exactly long enough to

312
00:29:17,280 --> 00:29:22,660
identify me laughing, and kept going down the corridor without saying anything. Narina gave me a

313
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:29,080
sweet kick on the foot under the bench. Sweetie, she whispered, mouthful, that man just looked at you

314
00:29:29,080 --> 00:29:34,240
the way you look at an open window in the middle of winter. Shut up, it's a professional observation.

315
00:29:35,040 --> 00:29:40,300
Your music teacher Narina. Music is observation, my girl. What do you think we listen to?

316
00:29:40,540 --> 00:29:45,940
I nudged her with my elbow. She laughed. Dona Chiara came back with a picture of water as if nothing

317
00:29:45,940 --> 00:29:52,280
had happened. I took a long sip and said nothing more. That night, when Narina left, the corridor was

318
00:29:52,280 --> 00:29:59,720
too silent. I passed the library door and saw the light on under the crack. I didn't go in. I went to my room,

319
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:05,540
closed the door, and took a long time to fall asleep. The kitchen was too big for crying at dawn.

320
00:30:05,920 --> 00:30:11,460
I discovered this three days later, on Monday, when I came down barefoot at three in the morning,

321
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:17,020
because I'd woken with my heart in my throat, and a dream of an empty church stuck to my neck.

322
00:30:17,020 --> 00:30:22,900
I turned on only the light above the stove. I sat on the cold floor with my back against the cabinet.

323
00:30:23,380 --> 00:30:28,260
The crying came without sound. The way I'd learned to cry when I lived with my grandmother,

324
00:30:28,880 --> 00:30:34,100
and she didn't like to hear sadness after ten at night. I heard the footsteps before I saw his

325
00:30:34,100 --> 00:30:39,120
shadow in the archway. He didn't turn on the main light. He stood there for two seconds in the door

326
00:30:39,120 --> 00:30:45,460
way. In a white shirt open at the collar. His hair sang he hadn't slept either. He didn't ask anything.

327
00:30:45,460 --> 00:30:49,860
I lifted my chin before he could think of touching me. I don't need an audience to cry.

328
00:30:50,360 --> 00:30:55,800
Thank you. He stopped in a very specific way, without retreating or advancing. He just stayed.

329
00:30:56,320 --> 00:31:01,320
Then, without saying a word, he crossed the kitchen, opened the cabinet beside my shoulder,

330
00:31:01,900 --> 00:31:07,220
and took out a glass. He filled the glass with water at the sink. He set the glass on the floor near my knee.

331
00:31:07,680 --> 00:31:12,960
He sat on the floor across from me. His back against the opposite cabinet. His legs stretched out

332
00:31:12,960 --> 00:31:19,080
in a way that made his feet almost touch mine. And he stayed. He didn't talk. He didn't ask.

333
00:31:19,580 --> 00:31:25,500
He didn't offer a shoulder. He stayed there. On the cold kitchen floor, with his rumpled shirt

334
00:31:25,500 --> 00:31:31,860
and his gaze on some point between my knee and the baseboard, breathing slowly. I cried for two more minutes.

335
00:31:32,340 --> 00:31:36,460
I drank half the glass. I cried a little more. I drank the rest.

336
00:31:36,860 --> 00:31:41,600
When I stood up, he stood up too, without touching me. He collected the glass.

337
00:31:41,600 --> 00:31:46,180
Carried it to the sink. Washed it with the same calm he did everything else.

338
00:31:46,560 --> 00:31:51,240
Good night, Ayolanda. I went back to my room and took a long time to fall asleep again,

339
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:55,520
but for another reason. The first public dinner came on Friday night.

340
00:31:55,980 --> 00:32:00,940
Il Juita Sole. A restaurant that served all of Providence without serving anyone properly,

341
00:32:01,540 --> 00:32:07,240
with a crystal chandelier and a mehta, who lowered his head half a degree when Ludovico entered.

342
00:32:07,240 --> 00:32:12,660
He'd told me at breakfast with a short sentence. In the way I already recognized as his way

343
00:32:12,660 --> 00:32:19,000
of asking without asking. Il Juita Sole, nine at night. It's important that we appear together.

344
00:32:19,540 --> 00:32:25,140
Dress? Whatever you think is good. I chose the dark blue one, the one with thin straps that

345
00:32:25,140 --> 00:32:29,080
fell to mid-caf. I put on the only pair of earrings I'd brought from the old department.

346
00:32:29,540 --> 00:32:34,120
I came down the stairs with my hair pinned at the nape and saw Ludovico waiting below

347
00:32:34,120 --> 00:32:38,740
in a black suit that looked like it had been cut on his body, and an expression he managed to

348
00:32:38,740 --> 00:32:46,720
keep closed for three seconds before looking away. Let's go. He said. At the restaurant, everyone looked.

349
00:32:47,200 --> 00:32:52,000
No one stared. We sat at a table near the back. The mait report the wine with slightly

350
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:57,200
trembling hands. Ludovico ordered for me without consulting me. A dish I wouldn't have ordered,

351
00:32:57,720 --> 00:33:02,900
and that was exactly the way I liked it. I raised an eyebrow. Does Donachiyara have a notebook of

352
00:33:02,900 --> 00:33:09,120
my records? I asked. She has a memory. Her memory is about me, about everyone who sits at her table.

353
00:33:09,640 --> 00:33:15,000
I took a sip. Ludovico, he looked up. Does this still feel more like a contract than a marriage?

354
00:33:15,480 --> 00:33:20,580
He held the glass by the stem, swirled the wine a quarter turn, set the glass back on the table

355
00:33:20,580 --> 00:33:27,160
without drinking. What would you rather it feel like? I don't know. I admitted. I'm still figuring it out.

356
00:33:27,160 --> 00:33:33,160
He almost smiled. Almost. It was at that moment that Renolfo Saravale crossed the restaurant.

357
00:33:33,640 --> 00:33:38,300
I didn't know who he was. I only felt the restaurant changed temperature before he reached the

358
00:33:38,300 --> 00:33:44,540
table. Ludovico stiffened half a degree. Enough for me to notice. Not enough for anyone else to notice.

359
00:33:45,080 --> 00:33:50,700
Renolfo was a man in a light suit, a wide smile and heavy shoulders, with a colabrian accent

360
00:33:50,700 --> 00:33:56,920
that dragged the consonants in a strange way. Ludovico, what a nice surprise. Renolfo,

361
00:33:57,420 --> 00:34:02,880
and this must be the new Mrs. Caracciolo. Renolfo turned to me with theatrical courtesy and extended

362
00:34:02,880 --> 00:34:08,820
his hand and immense pleasure. Before I could decide what to do with my hand, Ludovico simply looked

363
00:34:08,820 --> 00:34:15,120
at him. He didn't speak. He didn't move. He just looked. The look lasted exactly the length of one

364
00:34:15,120 --> 00:34:20,560
breath and Renolfo understood. He withdrew his hand with the smile still hanging on his face,

365
00:34:20,920 --> 00:34:25,440
in the way of a man who knows he's lost this round and that the next subject is better left

366
00:34:25,440 --> 00:34:32,100
